bd154c5f-4c3b-4aa3-b173-9e46ce53f0b9	00298f6e-70e4-49ee-8fd8-b7907e648ea7	\N	Surveillance	high	Entrances and POS lack forensic identification capability	The current assessment highlights high shoplifting/ORC exposure without evidence of camera performance tuned for person or event attribution at entrances and point-of-sale. Without sufficient facial and clothing detail, cases are difficult to investigate and prosecute.	Upgrade entrance and POS viewpoints to deliver forensic identification capability equivalent to at least 46 Px/ft, with 35 Px/ft across primary aisles for recognition. Provide 70 Px/ft at any alley/loading view used for license plates and 88 Px/ft at the main door if watchlist comparison is desired. Target 1530 fps, wide dynamic range, and 90 days retention. Reference: IEC 62676-4 (image detail guidance); apply the pixel-density thresholds provided; align system design with ANSI/ASIS RA.1-2015 risk-driven requirements.	7	8	56	Critical	\N	\N	\N	2025-12-09 02:00:49.627401
644f9ada-cbd7-4421-b3d0-5ca85eaa7e13	00298f6e-70e4-49ee-8fd8-b7907e648ea7	\N	Lighting Systems	medium	Inadequate forensic identification lighting at storefront and sales floor	Without documented illumination performance, facial detail and color fidelity may be insufficient for reliable incident investigation after dark or in high-contrast conditions, degrading video evidence quality.	Achieve vertical illumination for identification at public entries of 2.0 fc minimum; maintain 1.0 fc for recognition across sales floor and 0.5 fc for detection in back-of-house. For adjacent parking structures or garages used by staff/customers, target 5 fc average with 4:1 uniformity ratio. Use high-CRI LED and minimize glare at camera views. Reference: lighting thresholds provided; align with IES guidance for retail/parking; integrate with IEC 62676-4 to ensure lighting supports camera performance.	5	6	30	High	\N	\N	\N	2025-12-09 02:00:49.627401
df42f77c-0a69-4be1-a992-5e4d41881cd4	00298f6e-70e4-49ee-8fd8-b7907e648ea7	\N	Access Control	medium	Employee-only and stock areas lack anti-forced entry protection and controlled entry	Open retail environments require hardened separation between public space and merchandise storage. The assessment provides no evidence of credential-based control or intrusion monitoring for stockrooms, creating a pathway for internal theft and ORC staging.	Install electronic entry control for back-of-house/stock areas with anti-forced entry protection, door position monitoring, and alarm-on-prop rules integrated to video verification. Apply balanced designensure detection, delay, and response are commensurate. Reference: ANSI/ASIS PAP.1-2012 (R2017) Physical Asset Protection; ANSI/ASIS RA.1-2015 risk-based control selection.	6	5	30	High	\N	\N	\N	2025-12-09 02:00:49.627401
00e447f6-9720-41e6-8763-94152ad16ce3	00298f6e-70e4-49ee-8fd8-b7907e648ea7	\N	Loss Prevention Technology	high	No electronic article surveillance system documented	Given high shoplifting/ORC likelihood, the absence of a documented merchandise exit-screening capability increases shrink exposure and reduces deterrence at doors.	Deploy an electronic article surveillance system with dual-pedestal coverage at main exits, integrated alarms, and source tagging for high-loss SKUs. Calibrate to minimize nuisance alarms and integrate events with video bookmarks for investigations. Reference: ANSI/ASIS PAP.1-2012 (R2017) for protective measure selection; apply balanced detection and response.	8	7	56	Critical	\N	\N	\N	2025-12-09 02:00:49.627401
5f609ccc-259f-4c14-99ce-d717135923e2	00298f6e-70e4-49ee-8fd8-b7907e648ea7	\N	Retail Operations	high	Lack of transaction auditing capability at point-of-sale	Without exception-based reporting tied to video, refund/void abuse, sweethearting, and scan avoidance are difficult to detect, sustaining margin erosion.	Implement exception-based reporting with video association for POS, including alerts for high-risk events (no-sale, returns, voids, price overrides). Integrate with case management and schedule weekly analytics reviews. Reference: ANSI/ASIS INV.1-2015 Investigations; ANSI/ASIS RA.1-2015 control effectiveness monitoring.	6	7	42	High	\N	\N	\N	2025-12-09 02:00:49.627401
f21e8c63-d34b-4b23-8677-35b87110f639	00298f6e-70e4-49ee-8fd8-b7907e648ea7	\N	Barriers	medium	Sales floor lacks anti-sweep merchandising protections	Open-sell displays for high-value items without delay features enable rapid grab-and-run events by ORC crews.	Introduce shelf-edge retention, time-release hooks, discreet tethers, and quick-service locking displays for high-loss SKUs; anchor fixtures near exits and create a controlled exit path with pushout-prevention fixtures where permissible. Reference: ANSI/ASIS PAP.1-2012 (R2017) and balanced design principles (DetectionDelayResponse).	7	7	49	Critical	\N	\N	\N	2025-12-09 02:00:49.627401
6e911eaf-5c14-49bf-9ad6-8c0ed5d203dd	00298f6e-70e4-49ee-8fd8-b7907e648ea7	\N	Response and Monitoring	medium	Delayed response to in-store events reduces the value of detection	Detection without rapid, safe response allows offenders to exit before engagement or evidence capture. The assessment provides no defined response time targets or escalation paths.	Establish a 3-minute in-store response objective supported by remote monitoring alerts, staff de-escalation training, and ORC playbooks. Coordinate with local police for prioritized call types and share digital evidence packages. Reference: ANSI/ASIS ORM.1-2017 Security and Resilience for response planning; ANSI/ASIS INV.1-2015 for evidence handling.	7	6	42	High	\N	\N	\N	2025-12-09 02:00:49.627401
a63fb760-505f-4c4f-adf0-bfe5e4df7881	00298f6e-70e4-49ee-8fd8-b7907e648ea7	\N	Cyber-Physical Security	low	Video and access systems lack explicit hardening requirements	If cameras and controllers reside on the corporate network without segmentation and credential standards, adversaries could disable detection or delete evidence.	Apply network segmentation, strong authentication, timely patching, and audit logging for all security devices; restrict remote access and encrypt evidence exports. Reference: ANSI/ASIS RA.1-2015 for risk-based control selection; NIST SP 800-82/800-53 for control baselines applicable to operational systems.	5	4	20	Medium	\N	\N	\N	2025-12-09 02:00:49.627401
252a40d7-4c75-430f-86d1-b42a6e2f9f33	00298f6e-70e4-49ee-8fd8-b7907e648ea7	\N	Power and Redundancy	low	Insufficient continuity for critical detection and recording	Power interruptions common to urban grids can degrade surveillance, access control, and EAS at the most critical moments.	Provide battery backup to sustain cameras, recorders, EAS, and entry control for a minimum of 3060 minutes, with supervised health monitoring. Reference: ANSI/ASIS PAP.1-2012 (R2017) redundancy and fail-safe principles.	4	5	20	Medium	\N	\N	\N	2025-12-09 02:00:49.627401
8bb55059-f2a3-4400-a955-04c94902e650	00298f6e-70e4-49ee-8fd8-b7907e648ea7	\N	Governance and Risk	medium	Risk rating inconsistency with threat indicators	The scenario labels risk as low despite high likelihood and moderate impact. This misclassification can depress investment and enable continued shrink.	Adopt a calibrated scoring model per ANSI/ASIS RA.1-2015 that weights frequency and financial impact, and validate with 612 months of incident and shrink data. Re-baseline quarterly.	6	6	36	High	\N	\N	\N	2025-12-09 02:00:49.627401
